# Positive Peak Clamper (Negative Reference)

## Input
- Square wave signal (~4 Hz)
- Negative DC reference applied

## Output Observations
- The waveform is still shifted upward, but less compared to the positive reference case
- The negative peaks are clamped at a voltage below 0V
- The overall DC shift is reduced due to the negative reference
- The waveform shape remains unchanged

## Explanation
- During the negative half-cycle, the diode conducts and charges the capacitor considering the negative reference voltage
- During the positive half-cycle, the diode is reverse biased
- The capacitor stores a reduced voltage due to the negative reference
- This results in a smaller upward shift of the waveform

## Conclusion
Applying a negative reference lowers the clamping level below 0V, reducing the upward shift of the waveform compared to the no-reference case.
